# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: single-page-application
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:single-page-application/ajax-programming] Ajax is not a technology, but rather a programming pattern.
[src:single-page-application/ajax-programming] HTML and CSS can be used in combination to mark up and style information.
[src:single-page-application/ajax-programming] The webpage can be modified by JavaScript to dynamically display (and allow the user to interact with) the new information.
[src:single-page-application/ajax-programming] The built-in XMLHttpRequest object is used to execute Ajax on webpages, allowing websites to load content onto the screen without refreshing the page.
[src:single-page-application/ajax-programming] In the early-to-mid 1990s, most websites were based on complete HTML pages.
[src:single-page-application/ajax-programming] Each user action required a complete new page to be loaded from the server.
[src:single-page-application/ajax-programming] This process was inefficient, as reflected by the user experience: all page content disappeared, then the new page appeared.
[src:single-page-application/ajax-programming] Each time the browser reloaded a page because of a partial change, all the content had to be re-sent, even though only some of the information had changed.
[src:single-page-application/ajax-programming] This placed additional load on the server and made bandwidth a limiting factor in performance.
[src:single-page-application/ajax-programming] The foundations of AJAX originate back in 1996 with the introduction of JavaScript 1.
[src:single-page-application/ajax-programming] Developers quickly discovered that any HTML element which accepted a "src" attribute could be used to fetch remote data.
[src:single-page-application/ajax-programming] By changing the src of a hidden frame, a developer could fetch remote data, process or display it without a page refresh.
[src:single-page-application/ajax-programming] The remote data could be a string, JavaScript code, XML or a partial HTML page generated on the server.
[src:single-page-application/ajax-programming] The same could be done with `<img>` and `<embed>` tags, but many developers were alarmed at the concept of an executable GIF and preferred to use the hidden `<iframe>`.
[src:single-page-application/ajax-programming] This technique was used for both Netscape Navigator and Internet Explorer, the two main browsers at the time, until developers discovered the XMLHTTP server object (MSXML 1.0) was included in Internet Explorer 4.
[src:single-page-application/ajax-programming] Browser detection was then used to either implement the hidden `<iframe>` in Netscape or use the XMLHTTP (MSXML 1.0) object in IE 4.
[src:single-page-application/ajax-programming] In 1996, the iframe tag was introduced by Internet Explorer; like the object element, it can load a part of the web page asynchronously.
[src:single-page-application/ajax-programming] In 1998, the Microsoft Outlook Web Access team developed the concept behind the XMLHttpRequest scripting object.
[src:single-page-application/ajax-programming] It appeared as XMLHTTP in the second version of the MSXML library, which shipped with Internet Explorer 5.0 in March 1999.
[src:single-page-application/ajax-programming] The functionality of the Windows XMLHTTP ActiveX control in IE 5 was later implemented by Mozilla Firefox, Safari, Opera, Google Chrome, and other browsers as the XMLHttpRequest JavaScript object.
[src:single-page-application/ajax-programming] Microsoft adopted the native XMLHttpRequest model as of Internet Explorer 7.
[src:single-page-application/ajax-programming] Support for the ActiveX version remained in Internet Explorer and on "Internet Explorer mode" in Microsoft Edge.
[src:single-page-application/ajax-programming] The utility of these background HTTP requests and asynchronous Web technologies remained fairly obscure until it started appearing in large scale online applications such as Outlook Web Access (2000) and Oddpost (2002).
[src:single-page-application/ajax-programming] Google made a wide deployment of standards-compliant, cross browser Ajax with Gmail (2004) and Google Maps (2005).
[src:single-page-application/ajax-programming] In October 2004 Kayak.com's public beta release was among the first large-scale e-commerce uses of what their developers at that time called "the xml http thing".
[src:single-page-application/ajax-programming] This increased interest in Ajax among web program developers.
[src:single-page-application/ajax-programming] The term *AJAX* was publicly used on 18 February 2005 by Jesse James Garrett in an article titled *Ajax: A New Approach to Web Applications*, based on techniques used on Google pages.
[src:single-page-application/ajax-programming] On 5 April 2006, the World Wide Web Consortium (W3C) released the first draft specification for the XMLHttpRequest object in an attempt to create an official Web standard.
[src:single-page-application/ajax-programming] The latest draft of the XMLHttpRequest object was published on 6 October 2016, and the XMLHttpRequest specification is now a living standard.
[src:single-page-application/ajax-programming] The term *Ajax* has come to represent a broad group of Web technologies that can be used to implement a Web application that communicates with a server in the background, without interfering with the current state of the page.
[src:single-page-application/ajax-programming] Since then, however, there have been a number of developments in the technologies used in an Ajax application, and in the definition of the term Ajax itself.
[src:single-page-application/ajax-programming] XML is no longer required for data interchange and, therefore, XSLT is no longer required for the manipulation of data.
[src:single-page-application/ajax-programming] JavaScript Object Notation (JSON) is often used as an alternative format for data interchange, although other formats such as preformatted HTML or plain text can also be used.
[src:single-page-application/ajax-programming] A variety of popular JavaScript libraries, including jQuery, include abstractions to assist in executing Ajax requests.
[src:single-page-application/ajax-programming] An example of a simple Ajax request using the GET method, written in JavaScript.
[src:single-page-application/ajax-programming] Ajax offers several benefits that can significantly enhance web application performance and user experience.
[src:single-page-application/ajax-programming] By reducing server traffic and improving speed, Ajax plays a crucial role in modern web development.
[src:single-page-application/ajax-programming] One key advantage of Ajax is its capacity to render web applications without requiring data retrieval, resulting in reduced server traffic.
[src:single-page-application/ajax-programming] This optimization minimizes response times on both the server and client sides, eliminating the need for users to endure loading screens.
[src:single-page-application/ajax-programming] Furthermore, Ajax facilitates asynchronous processing by simplifying the utilization of XmlHttpRequest, which enables efficient handling of requests for asynchronous data retrieval.
[src:single-page-application/ajax-programming] Additionally, the dynamic loading of content enhances the application's performance significantly.
[src:single-page-application/ajax-programming] Besides, Ajax enjoys broad support across all major web browsers, including Microsoft Internet Explorer versions 5 and above, Mozilla Firefox versions 1.0 and beyond, Opera versions 7.6 and above, and Apple Safari versions 1.2 and higher.
[src:single-page-application/api-history-api] This feature is well established and works across many devices and browser versions.
[src:single-page-application/api-history-api] It’s been available across browsers since July 2015.
[src:single-page-application/api-history-api] The **History API** provides access to the browser's session history (not to be confused with WebExtensions history) through the `history` global object.
[src:single-page-application/api-history-api] It exposes useful methods and properties that let you navigate back and forth through the user's history, and manipulate the contents of the history stack.
[src:single-page-application/api-history-api] Moving backward and forward through the user's history is done using the `back()`, `forward()`, and `go()` methods.
[src:single-page-application/api-history-api] This acts exactly as if the user clicked on the **Back** button in their browser toolbar.
[src:single-page-application/api-history-api] You can use the `go()` method to load a specific page from session history, identified by its relative position to the current page.
[src:single-page-application/api-history-api] Similarly, you can move forward 2 pages by passing `2`, and so forth.
[src:single-page-application/api-history-api] Allows manipulation of the browser *session history* (that is, the pages visited in the tab or frame that the current page is loaded in).
[src:single-page-application/api-history-api] The following example assigns a listener for the `popstate` event.
[src:single-page-application/api-history-api] It then illustrates some of the methods of the history object to add, replace, and move within the browser history for the current tab.
[src:single-page-application/api-history] The **`History`** interface of the History API allows manipulation of the browser *session history*, that is the pages visited in the tab or frame that the current page is loaded in.
[src:single-page-application/api-history] There is only one instance of `history` (It is a *singleton*.) accessible via the global object `history`.
[src:single-page-application/api-history] Returns an `Integer` representing the number of elements in the session history, including the currently loaded page.
[src:single-page-application/api-history] For example, for a page loaded in a new tab this property returns `1`.
[src:single-page-application/api-history] Allows web applications to explicitly set default scroll restoration behavior on history navigation.
[src:single-page-application/api-history] This property can be either `auto` or `manual`.
[src:single-page-application/api-history] Returns an `any` value representing the state at the top of the history stack.
[src:single-page-application/api-history] This is a way to look at the state without having to wait for a `popstate` event.
[src:single-page-application/api-history] This asynchronous method goes to the previous page in session history, the same action as when the user clicks the browser's Back button.
[src:single-page-application/api-history] Calling this method to go back beyond the first page in the session history has no effect and doesn't raise an exception.
[src:single-page-application/api-history] This asynchronous method goes to the next page in session history, the same action as when the user clicks the browser's Forward button; this is equivalent to `history.go(1)`.
[src:single-page-application/api-history] Calling this method to go forward beyond the most recent page in the session history has no effect and doesn't raise an exception.
[src:single-page-application/api-history] Asynchronously loads a page from the session history, identified by its relative location to the current page, for example `-1` for the previous page or `1` for the next page.
[src:single-page-application/api-history] If you specify an out-of-bounds value (for instance, specifying `-1` when there are no previously-visited pages in the session history), this method silently has no effect.
[src:single-page-application/api-history] Calling `go()` without parameters or a value of `0` reloads the current page.
[src:single-page-application/api-history] Pushes the given data onto the session history stack with the specified title (and, if provided, URL).
[src:single-page-application/api-history] The data is treated as opaque by the DOM; you may specify any JavaScript object that can be serialized.
[src:single-page-application/api-history] Note that all browsers but Safari currently ignore the *title* parameter.
[src:single-page-application/api-history] For more information, see Working with the History API.
[src:single-page-application/api-history] Updates the most recent entry on the history stack to have the specified data, title, and, if provided, URL.
[src:single-page-application/navigation-api] Since January 2026, this feature works across the latest devices and browser versions.
[src:single-page-application/navigation-api] This feature might not work in older devices or browsers.
[src:single-page-application/navigation-api] The **Navigation API** provides the ability to initiate, intercept, and manage browser navigation actions.
[src:single-page-application/navigation-api] It can also examine an application's history entries.
[src:single-page-application/navigation-api] This is a successor to previous web platform features such as the History API and `window.location`, which solves their shortcomings and is specifically aimed at the needs of single-page applications (SPAs).
[src:single-page-application/navigation-api] In SPAs, the page template tends to stay the same during usage, and the content is dynamically rewritten as the user visits different pages or features.
[src:single-page-application/navigation-api] As a result, only one distinct page is loaded in the browser, which breaks the expected user experience of navigating back and forth between different locations in the viewing history.
[src:single-page-application/navigation-api] This problem can be solved to a degree via the History API, but it is not designed for the needs of SPAs.
[src:single-page-application/navigation-api] The Navigation API aims to bridge that gap.
[src:single-page-application/navigation-api] The API is accessed via the `Window.navigation` property, which returns a reference to a global `Navigation` object.
[src:single-page-application/navigation-api] Each `window` object has its own corresponding `navigation` instance.
[src:single-page-application/navigation-api] The `navigation` interface has several associated events, the most notable being the `navigate` event.
[src:single-page-application/navigation-api] This is fired when any type of navigation is initiated, meaning that you can control all page navigations from one central place, ideal for routing functionality in SPA frameworks.
[src:single-page-application/navigation-api] Once a navigation is initiated, and your `intercept()` handler is called, a `NavigationTransition` object instance is created (accessible via `Navigation.transition`), which can be used to track the process of the ongoing navigation.
[src:single-page-application/navigation-api] When the promises returned by the `intercept()` handler functions fulfill, the `Navigation` object's `navigatesuccess` event fires, allowing you to run cleanup code after a successful navigation has completed.
[src:single-page-application/navigation-api] If they reject, meaning the navigation has failed, `navigateerror` fires instead, allowing you to gracefully handle failure case.
[src:single-page-application/navigation-api] There is also a `finished` property on the return value of navigation methods (such as `Navigation.navigate()`), which fulfills or rejects at the same time as the aforementioned events are fired, providing another path for handling the success and failure cases.
[src:single-page-application/navigation-api] As the user navigates through your application, each new location navigated to results in the creation of a navigation history entry.
[src:single-page-application/navigation-api] Each history entry is represented by a distinct `NavigationHistoryEntry` object instance.
[src:single-page-application/navigation-api] These contain several properties such as the entry's key, URL, and state information.
[src:single-page-application/navigation-api] You can get the entry that the user is currently on right now using `Navigation.currentEntry`, and an array of all existing history entries using `Navigation.entries()`.
[src:single-page-application/navigation-api] Each `NavigationHistoryEntry` object has a `dispose` event, which fires when the entry is no longer part of the browser history.
[src:single-page-application/navigation-api] For example, if the user navigates back three times, then navigates forward to somewhere else, those three history entries will be disposed of.
[src:single-page-application/navigation-api] Navigates to a new URL, creating a new navigation history entry.
[src:single-page-application/navigation-api] Reloads the current navigation history entry.
[src:single-page-application/navigation-api] Navigates to the previous navigation history entry, if that is possible.
[src:single-page-application/navigation-api] Navigates to the next navigation history entry, if that is possible.
[src:single-page-application/navigation-api] Navigates to a specific navigation history entry identified by its key value, which is obtained via the relevant entry's `NavigationHistoryEntry.key` property.
[src:single-page-application/navigation-api] Each one of the above methods returns an object containing two promises — `{ committed, finished }`.
[src:single-page-application/navigation-api] The Navigation API allows you to store state on each history entry.
[src:single-page-application/navigation-api] This is developer-defined information — it can be whatever you like.
[src:single-page-application/navigation-api] For example, you might want to store a `visitCount` property that records the number of times a view has been visited, or an object containing multiple properties related to UI state, so that state can be restored when a user returns to that view.
[src:single-page-application/navigation-api] To get a `NavigationHistoryEntry`'s state, you call its `getState()` method.
[src:single-page-application/navigation-api] It is initially `undefined`, but when state information is set on the entry, it will return the previously-set state information.
[src:single-page-application/navigation-api] You can't retrieve the state value and then update it directly — the copy stored on the entry will not change.
[src:single-page-application/navigation-api] Instead, you update it while performing a `navigate()` or `reload()` — each one of these optionally takes an options object parameter, which includes a `state` property containing the new state to set on the history entry.
[src:single-page-application/navigation-api] When these navigations commit, the state change will be automatically applied.
[src:single-page-application/navigation-api] In some cases however, a state change will be independent from a navigation or reload — for example when a page contains an expandable/collapsible `<details>` element.
[src:single-page-application/navigation-api] In this case, you might want to store the expanded/collapsed state in your history entry, so you can restore it when the user returns to the page or restarts their browser.
[src:single-page-application/navigation-api] Cases like this are handled using `Navigation.updateCurrentEntry()`.
[src:single-page-application/navigation-api] The `currententrychange` will fire when the current entry change is complete.
[src:single-page-application/navigation-api] The Navigation API operates only within a single frame—the top-level page, or a single specific `<iframe>`.
[src:single-page-application/navigation-api] This has some interesting implications that are further documented in the spec, but in practice, will reduce developer confusion.
[src:single-page-application/navigation-api] The previous History API has several confusing edge cases, like support for frames, which the Navigation API handles up-front.
[src:single-page-application/navigation-api] You can't currently use the Navigation API to programmatically modify or rearrange the history list.
[src:single-page-application/navigation-api] It might be useful to have a temporary state, for example navigating the user to a temporary modal that asks them for some information, then going back to the previous URL.
[src:single-page-application/navigation-api] In this case, you'd want to delete the temporary modal navigation entry so the user cannot mess up the application flow by hitting the forward button and opening it again.
[src:single-page-application/navigation-api] Event object for the `navigate` event, which fires when any type of navigation is initiated.
[src:single-page-application/navigation-api] It provides access to information about that navigation, and most notably the `intercept()`, which allows you to control what happens when the navigation is initiated.
[src:single-page-application/navigation-api] Allows control over all navigation actions for the current `window` in one central place, including initiating navigations programmatically, examining navigation history entries, and managing navigations as they happen.
[src:single-page-application/navigation-api] Represents a recent cross-document navigation.
[src:single-page-application/navigation-api] It contains the navigation type and current and destination document history entries.
[src:single-page-application/navigation-api] Event object for the `currententrychange` event, which fires when the `Navigation.currentEntry` has changed.
[src:single-page-application/navigation-api] It provides access to the navigation type, and the previous history entry that was navigated from.
[src:single-page-application/navigation-api] Represents the destination being navigated to in the current navigation.
[src:single-page-application/navigation-api] Represents a single navigation history entry.
[src:single-page-application/navigation-api] Defines redirect behavior for a navigation precommit handler, when passed into the `precommitHandler` callback of a `NavigateEvent.intercept()` method call.
[src:single-page-application/navigation-api] Returns the current `window`'s associated `Navigation` object.
[src:single-page-application/navigation-api] This is the entry point for the Navigation API.
[src:single-page-application/navigation-api] In this example of intercepting a navigation, the `handler()` function starts by fetching and rendering some article content, but then fetches and renders some secondary content afterwards.
[src:single-page-application/navigation-api] It makes sense to scroll the page to the main article content as soon as it is available so the user can interact with it, rather than waiting until the secondary content is also rendered.
[src:single-page-application/navigation-api] To achieve this, we have added a `scroll()` call between the two.
[src:single-page-application/popstate-event] The **`popstate`** event of the `Window` interface is fired when the active history entry changes while the user navigates the session history.
[src:single-page-application/popstate-event] It changes the current history entry to that of the last page the user visited or, if `history.pushState()` has been used to add a history entry to the history stack, that history entry is used instead.
[src:single-page-application/popstate-event] Use the event name in methods like `addEventListener()`, or set an event handler property.
[src:single-page-application/popstate-event] Returns a copy of the information that was provided to `pushState()` or `replaceState()`.
[src:single-page-application/popstate-event] If the history entry being activated was created by a call to `history.pushState()` or was affected by a call to `history.replaceState()`, the `popstate` event's `state` property contains a copy of the history entry's state object.
[src:single-page-application/popstate-event] These methods and their corresponding events can be used to add data to the history stack which can be used to reconstruct a dynamically generated page, or to otherwise alter the state of the content being presented while remaining on the same `Document`.
[src:single-page-application/popstate-event] Note that just calling `history.pushState()` or `history.replaceState()` won't trigger a `popstate` event.
[src:single-page-application/popstate-event] The `popstate` event will be triggered by doing a browser action such as a click on the back or forward button (or calling `history.back()` or `history.forward()` in JavaScript).
[src:single-page-application/popstate-event] It's important to first understand that — to combat unwanted pop-ups — browsers may not fire the `popstate` event at all unless the page has been interacted with.
[src:single-page-application/popstate-event] This section describes the steps that browsers follow in the cases where they *do* potentially fire the `popstate` event (that is, in the cases where the page has been interacted with).
[src:single-page-application/popstate-event] When a navigation occurs — either due to the user triggering the browser's Back button or otherwise — the `popstate` event is near the end of the process to navigate to the new location.
[src:single-page-application/popstate-event] It happens after the new location has loaded (if needed), displayed, made visible, and so on — after the `pageshow` event is sent, but before the persisted user state information is restored and the `hashchange` event is sent.
[src:single-page-application/popstate-event] To better understand when the `popstate` event is fired, consider this simplified sequence of events that occurs when the current history entry changes due to either the user navigating the site or the history being traversed programmatically.
[src:single-page-application/popstate-event] Here, the transition is changing the current history entry to one we'll refer to as **new-entry**.
[src:single-page-application/popstate-event] The current page's session history stack entry will be referred to as **current-entry**.
[src:single-page-application/popstate-event] If **current-entry**'s title wasn't set using one of the History API methods (`pushState()` or `replaceState()`), set the entry's title to the string returned by its `document.title` attribute.
[src:single-page-application/popstate-event] If the browser has state information it wishes to store with the **current-entry** before navigating away from it, it then does so.
[src:single-page-application/popstate-event] The entry is now said to have "persisted user state." This information the browser might add to the history session entry may include, for instance, the document's scroll position, the values of form inputs, and other such data.
[src:single-page-application/popstate-event] If **new-entry** has a different `Document` object than **current-entry**, the browsing context is updated so that its `document` property refers to the document referred to by **new-entry**, and the context's name is updated to match the context name of the now-current document.
[src:single-page-application/popstate-event] Each form control within **new-entry**'s `Document` that has `autocomplete` configured with its autofill field name set to `off` is reset.
[src:single-page-application/popstate-event] See The HTML autocomplete attribute for more about the autocomplete field names and how autocomplete works.
[src:single-page-application/popstate-event] If **new-entry**'s document is already fully loaded and ready—that is, its `readyState` is `complete`—and the document is not already visible, it's made visible and the `pageshow` event is fired at the document with the `PageTransitionEvent`'s `persisted` attribute set to `true`.
[src:single-page-application/popstate-event] The document's `URL` is set to that of **new-entry**.
[src:single-page-application/popstate-event] If the history traversal is being performed with replacement enabled, the entry immediately prior to the destination entry (taking into account the `delta` parameter on methods such as `go()`) is removed from the history stack.
[src:single-page-application/popstate-event] If the **new-entry** doesn't have persisted user state and its URL's fragment is non-`null`, the document is scrolled to that fragment.
[src:single-page-application/popstate-event] Next, **current-entry** is set to **new-entry**.
[src:single-page-application/popstate-event] The destination entry is now considered to be current.
[src:single-page-application/popstate-event] If **new-entry** has serialized state information saved with it, that information is deserialized into `History.state`; otherwise, `state` is `null`.
[src:single-page-application/popstate-event] If the value of `state` changed, the `popstate` event is sent to the document.
[src:single-page-application/popstate-event] Any persisted user state is restored, if the browser chooses to do so.
[src:single-page-application/popstate-event] If the original and new entries shared the same document, but had different fragments in their URLs, send the `hashchange` event to the window.
[src:single-page-application/popstate-event] As you can see, the `popstate` event is nearly the last thing done in the process of navigating pages in this way.
[src:single-page-application/popstate-event] Note that even though the original history entry (for `http://example.com/example.html`) has no state object associated with it, a `popstate` event is still fired when we activate that entry after the second call to `history.back()`.
[src:single-page-application/single-page-application] A **single-page application** (**SPA**) is a web application or website that interacts with the user by dynamically rewriting the current web page with new data from the web server, instead of the default method of loading entire new pages.
[src:single-page-application/single-page-application] The goal is faster transitions that make the website feel more like a native app.
[src:single-page-application/single-page-application] In a SPA, a page refresh never occurs; instead, all necessary HTML, JavaScript, and CSS code is either retrieved by the browser with a single page load, or the appropriate resources are dynamically loaded and added to the page as necessary, usually in response to user actions.
[src:single-page-application/single-page-application] The origins of the term *single-page application* are unclear, though the concept was discussed at least as early as 2003 by technology evangelists from Netscape.
[src:single-page-application/single-page-application] Earlier forms were called rich web applications.
[src:single-page-application/single-page-application] JavaScript can be used in a web browser to display the user interface (UI), run application logic, and communicate with a web server.
[src:single-page-application/single-page-application] Mature free libraries are available that support the building of a SPA, reducing the amount of JavaScript code developers have to write.
[src:single-page-application/single-page-application] There are various techniques available that enable the browser to retain a single page even when the application requires server communication.
[src:single-page-application/single-page-application] HTML authors can leverage element IDs to show or hide different sections of the HTML document.
[src:single-page-application/single-page-application] Then, using CSS, authors can use the `:target` pseudo-class selector to only show the section of the page which the browser navigated to.
[src:single-page-application/single-page-application] Web browser JavaScript frameworks and libraries, such as Angular, Ember.js, ExtJS, Knockout.js, Meteor.js, React, Vue.js, and Svelte have adopted SPA principles.
[src:single-page-application/single-page-application] Aside from ExtJS, all of these are free.
[src:single-page-application/single-page-application] JavaScript-based web application frameworks, such as React and Vue, provide extensive capabilities but come with associated trade-offs.
[src:single-page-application/single-page-application] These frameworks often extend or enhance features available through native web technologies, such as routing, component-based development, and state management.
[src:single-page-application/single-page-application] Frameworks can introduce abstraction layers that may contribute to performance overhead, larger bundle sizes, and increased complexity.
[src:single-page-application/single-page-application] Modern frameworks, such as React 18 and Vue 3, address these challenges with features like concurrent rendering, tree-shaking, and selective hydration.
[src:single-page-application/single-page-application] While these advancements improve rendering efficiency and resource management, their benefits depend on the specific application and implementation context.
[src:single-page-application/single-page-application] Lightweight frameworks, such as Svelte and Preact, take different architectural approaches, with Svelte eliminating the virtual DOM entirely in favor of compiling components to efficient JavaScript code, and Preact offering a minimal, compatible alternative to React.
[src:single-page-application/single-page-application] Framework choice depends on an application’s requirements, including the team’s expertise, performance goals, and development priorities.
[src:single-page-application/single-page-application] A newer category of web frameworks, including enhance.dev, Astro, and Fresh, leverages native web standards while minimizing abstractions and development tooling.
[src:single-page-application/single-page-application] These solutions emphasize progressive enhancement, server-side rendering, and optimizing performance.
[src:single-page-application/single-page-application] Astro renders static HTML by default while hydrating only interactive parts.
[src:single-page-application/single-page-application] Fresh focuses on server-side rendering with zero runtime overhead.
[src:single-page-application/single-page-application] Enhance.dev prioritizes progressive enhancement patterns using Web Components.
[src:single-page-application/single-page-application] While these tools reduce reliance on client-side JavaScript by shifting logic to build-time or server-side execution, they still use JavaScript where necessary for interactivity.
[src:single-page-application/single-page-application] This approach makes them particularly suitable for performance-critical and content-focused applications.
[src:single-page-application/single-page-application] The following frameworks utilize WebAssembly or can build single-page applications (SPAs) with WebAssembly as a core technology or support mechanism.
[src:single-page-application/single-page-application] These frameworks enable high-performance and interactive client-side development, extending the SPA paradigm across languages and ecosystems.
[src:single-page-application/single-page-application] As of 2006, the most prominent technique used was Ajax.
[src:single-page-application/single-page-application] Ajax involves using asynchronous requests to a server for XML or JSON data, such as with JavaScript's XMLHttpRequest or more modern `fetch()` (since 2017), or the deprecated ActiveX Object.
[src:single-page-application/single-page-application] In contrast to the declarative approach of most SPA frameworks, with Ajax the website directly uses JavaScript or a JavaScript library such as jQuery to manipulate the DOM and edit HTML elements.
[src:single-page-application/single-page-application] Ajax has further been popularized by libraries like jQuery, which provides a simpler syntax and normalizes Ajax behavior across different browsers which historically had varying behavior.
[src:single-page-application/single-page-application] WebSockets are a bidirectional real-time client-server communication technology that are part of the HTML specification.
[src:single-page-application/single-page-application] For real-time communication, their use is superior to Ajax in terms of performance and simplicity.
[src:single-page-application/single-page-application] Server-sent events (SSEs) is a technique whereby servers can initiate data transmission to browser clients.
[src:single-page-application/single-page-application] Once an initial connection has been established, an event stream remains open until closed by the client.
[src:single-page-application/single-page-application] SSEs are sent over traditional HTTP and have a variety of features that WebSockets lack by design such as automatic reconnection, event IDs, and the ability to send arbitrary events.
[src:single-page-application/single-page-application] Although this method is outdated, asynchronous calls to the server may also be achieved using browser plug-in technologies such as Silverlight, Flash, or Java applets.
[src:single-page-application/single-page-application] Requests to the server typically result in either raw data (e.g., XML or JSON), or new HTML being returned.
[src:single-page-application/single-page-application] In the case where HTML is returned by the server, JavaScript on the client updates a partial area of the DOM (Document Object Model).
[src:single-page-application/single-page-application] When raw data is returned, JavaScript on the client translates it into HTML using XSL or a JSON template before updating the DOM.
[src:single-page-application/single-page-application] A SPA moves logic from the server to the client, with the role of the web server evolving into a pure data API or web service.
[src:single-page-application/single-page-application] This architectural shift has, in some circles, been coined "Thin Server Architecture" to highlight that complexity has been moved from the server to the client, with the argument that this ultimately reduces overall complexity of the system.
[src:single-page-application/single-page-application] The server keeps the necessary state in memory of the client state of the page.
[src:single-page-application/single-page-application] In this way, when any request hits the server (usually user actions), the server sends the appropriate HTML and/or JavaScript with the concrete changes to bring the client to the new desired state (usually adding/deleting/updating a part of the client DOM).
[src:single-page-application/single-page-application] At the same time, the state in server is updated.
[src:single-page-application/single-page-application] Most of the logic is executed on the server, and HTML is usually also rendered on the server.
[src:single-page-application/single-page-application] In some ways, the server simulates a web browser, receiving events and performing delta changes in server state which are automatically propagated to client.
[src:single-page-application/single-page-application] This is a variant of the stateful server approach.
[src:single-page-application/single-page-application] The client page sends data representing its current state to the server, usually through Ajax requests.
[src:single-page-application/single-page-application] This approach requires that more data be sent to the server and may require more computational resources per request to partially or fully reconstruct the client page state in the server.
[src:single-page-application/single-page-application] At the same time, this approach is more easily scalable because there is no per-client page data kept in the server and, therefore, Ajax requests can be dispatched to different server nodes with no need for session data sharing or server affinity.
[src:single-page-application/single-page-application] Some SPAs may be executed from a local file using the file URI scheme.
[src:single-page-application/single-page-application] This gives users the ability to download the SPA from a server and run the file from a local storage device, without depending on server connectivity.
[src:single-page-application/single-page-application] If such a SPA wants to store and update data, it must use browser-based Web Storage.
[src:single-page-application/single-page-application] These applications benefit from advances available with HTML.
[src:single-page-application/single-page-application] Because the SPA is an evolution away from the stateless page-redraw model that browsers were originally designed for, some new challenges have emerged.
[src:single-page-application/single-page-application] Because of the lack of JavaScript execution on crawlers of some popular Web search engines, SEO (search engine optimization) has historically presented a problem for public facing websites wishing to adopt the SPA model.
[src:single-page-application/single-page-application] Between 2009 and 2015, Google Webmaster Central proposed and then recommended an "AJAX crawling scheme" using an initial exclamation mark in fragment identifiers for stateful AJAX pages (`#!`).
[src:single-page-application/single-page-application] Special behavior must be implemented by the SPA site to allow extraction of relevant metadata by the search engine's crawler.
[src:single-page-application/single-page-application] For search engines that do not support this URL hash scheme, the hashed URLs of the SPA remain invisible.
[src:single-page-application/single-page-application] These "hash-bang" URIs have been considered problematic by a number of writers including Jeni Tennison at the W3C because they make pages inaccessible to those who do not have JavaScript activated in their browser.
[src:single-page-application/single-page-application] They also break HTTP referer headers as browsers are not allowed to send the fragment identifier in the Referer header.
[src:single-page-application/single-page-application] In 2015, Google deprecated their hash-bang AJAX crawling proposal.
[src:single-page-application/single-page-application] Alternatively, applications may render the first page load on the server and subsequent page updates on the client.
[src:single-page-application/single-page-application] This is traditionally difficult, because the rendering code might need to be written in a different language or framework on the server and in the client.
[src:single-page-application/single-page-application] Using logic-less templates, cross-compiling from one language to another, or using the same language on the server and the client may help to increase the amount of code that can be shared.
[src:single-page-application/single-page-application] In 2018, Google introduced dynamic rendering as another option for sites wishing to offer crawlers a non-JavaScript heavy version of a page for indexing purposes.
[src:single-page-application/single-page-application] Dynamic rendering switches between a version of a page that is rendered client-side and a pre-rendered version for specific user agents.
[src:single-page-application/single-page-application] This approach involves your web server detecting crawlers (via the user agent) and routing them to a renderer, from which they are then served a simpler version of HTML content.
[src:single-page-application/single-page-application] As of 2024, Google no longer recommends dynamic rendering, suggesting "server-side rendering, static rendering, or hydration" instead.
[src:single-page-application/single-page-application] Because SEO compatibility is not trivial in SPAs, SPAs are commonly not used in a context where search engine indexing is either a requirement, or desirable.
[src:single-page-application/single-page-application] Use cases include applications that surface private data hidden behind an authentication system.
[src:single-page-application/single-page-application] In the cases where these applications are consumer products, often a classic "page redraw" model is used for the applications landing page and marketing site, which provides enough meta data for the application to appear as a hit in a search engine query.
[src:single-page-application/single-page-application] Blogs, support forums, and other traditional page redraw artifacts often sit around the SPA that can seed search engines with relevant terms.
[src:single-page-application/single-page-application] As of 2021 and Google specifically, SEO compatibility for a plain SPA is straightforward and requires just a few simple conditions to be met.
[src:single-page-application/single-page-application] One way to increase the amount of code that can be shared between servers and clients is to use a logic-less template language like Mustache or Handlebars.
[src:single-page-application/single-page-application] Such templates can be rendered from different host languages, such as Ruby on the server and JavaScript in the client.
[src:single-page-application/single-page-application] However, merely sharing templates typically requires duplication of business logic used to choose the correct templates and populate them with data.
[src:single-page-application/single-page-application] Rendering from templates may have negative performance effects when only updating a small portion of the page—such as the value of a text input within a large template.
[src:single-page-application/single-page-application] Replacing an entire template might also disturb a user's selection or cursor position, where updating only the changed value might not.
[src:single-page-application/single-page-application] To avoid these problems, applications can use UI data bindings or granular DOM manipulation to only update the appropriate parts of the page instead of re-rendering entire templates.
[src:single-page-application/single-page-application] With a SPA being, by definition, "a single page", the model breaks the browser's design for page history navigation using the "forward" or "back" buttons.
[src:single-page-application/single-page-application] This presents a usability impediment when a user presses the back button, expecting the previous screen state within the SPA, but instead, the application's single page unloads and the previous page in the browser's history is presented.
[src:single-page-application/single-page-application] The traditional solution for SPAs has been to change the browser URL's hash fragment identifier in accord with the current screen state.
[src:single-page-application/single-page-application] This can be achieved with JavaScript, and causes URL history events to be built up within the browser.
[src:single-page-application/single-page-application] As long as the SPA is capable of resurrecting the same screen state from information contained within the URL hash, the expected back-button behavior is retained.
[src:single-page-application/single-page-application] To further address this issue, the HTML specification has introduced pushState and replaceState providing programmatic access to the actual URL and browser history.
[src:single-page-application/single-page-application] Analytics tools such as Google Analytics rely heavily upon entire new pages loading in the browser, initiated by a new page load.
[src:single-page-application/single-page-application] After the first page load, all subsequent page and content changes are handled internally by the application, which should simply call a function to update the analytics package.
[src:single-page-application/single-page-application] Failing to call such a function, the browser never triggers a new page load, nothing gets added to the browser history, and the analytics package has no idea who is doing what on the site.
[src:single-page-application/single-page-application] Similarly to the problems encountered with search engine crawlers, DAST tools may struggle with these JavaScript-rich applications.
[src:single-page-application/single-page-application] Problems can include the lack of hypertext links, memory usage concerns and resources loaded by the SPA typically being made available by an Application Programming Interface or API.
[src:single-page-application/single-page-application] Single-page applications are still subject to the same security risks as traditional web pages such as Cross-Site Scripting (XSS), but also a host of other unique vulnerabilities such as data exposure via API and client-side logic and client-side enforcement of server-side security.
[src:single-page-application/single-page-application] In order to effectively scan a single-page application, a DAST scanner must be able to navigate the client-side application in a reliable and repeatable manner to allow discovery of all areas of the application and interception of all requests that the application sends to remote servers (e.g.
[src:single-page-application/single-page-application] It is possible to add page load events to a SPA using the HTML History API; this will help integrate analytics.
[src:single-page-application/single-page-application] The difficulty comes in managing this and ensuring that everything is being tracked accurately – this involves checking for missing reports and double entries.
[src:single-page-application/single-page-application] Some frameworks provide free analytics integrations addressing most of the major analytics providers.
[src:single-page-application/single-page-application] Developers can integrate them into the application and make sure that everything is working correctly, but there is no need to do everything from scratch.
[src:single-page-application/single-page-application] There are some ways of speeding up the initial load of a SPA, such as selective prerendering of the SPA landing/index page, caching and various code splitting techniques including lazy-loading modules when needed.
[src:single-page-application/single-page-application] But it's not possible to get away from the fact that it needs to download the framework, at least some of the application code; and will hit an API for data if the page is dynamic.
[src:single-page-application/single-page-application] This is a "pay me now, or pay me later" trade-off scenario.
[src:single-page-application/single-page-application] The question of performance and wait-times remains a decision that the developer must make.
[src:single-page-application/single-page-application] A SPA is fully loaded in the initial page load and then page regions are replaced or updated with new page fragments loaded from the server on demand.
[src:single-page-application/single-page-application] To avoid excessive downloading of unused features, a SPA will often progressively download more features as they become required, either small fragments of the page, or complete screen modules.
[src:single-page-application/single-page-application] In this way an analogy exists between "states" in a SPA and "pages" in a traditional website.
[src:single-page-application/single-page-application] Because "state navigation" in the same page is analogous to page navigation, in theory, any page-based web site could be converted to single-page replacing in the same page only the changed parts.
[src:single-page-application/single-page-application] The SPA approach on the web is similar to the single-document interface (SDI) presentation technique popular in native desktop applications.
